post_text: This was the first day of our successful in-person Extended School Year program. Six weeks later we can all be proud of being one of a few districts in NYS that offered a daily in-person program for students who qualified. No one was happier than the students. They wore their masks and stayed physically distanced. They learned and grew tremendously. Thank you to our wonderful staff! We are proud of our students!

post_text:
Each year, the Tuckahoe Union Free School District honors and pays tribute to those men and women who have made the Supreme Sacrifice for our country. This year, our virtual Memorial Day Commemoration Program will be held Friday, May 22, at 9 a.m.

Under the leadership of our dedicated administrators and music teachers, Tuckahoe students will thank all our veterans for their service. This year’s program will have a special significance as we also honor our First Responders and Healthcare and Essential workers as they ensure our country remains safe during these unprecedented times. Our entire district music department is joining forces to create a finale for our virtual Memorial Day Ceremony. It will include chorus students from all three schools, as well as instrumentalists from our MS/HS Band and Orchestra. This will be available on our website after the initial presentation. Please watch for an email for the link to view the event at 9:00 this Friday.

post_text:
Wellness Wednesday Tip from Health Teacher, Mr. Colasuonno: Complete 15 minutes of stress management activities daily.
Here are two helpful strategies:
Guided meditation is simply "meditation with the help of a guide". It’s one of the easiest ways to enter into a state of deep relaxation and inner stillness, and it’s one of the most powerful ways to eliminate stress and bring about positive personal changes. Use UCLA Guided Meditation, https://www.uclahealth.org/marc/mindful-meditations, or another favorite.
Progressive muscle relaxation is a deep relaxation technique that has been effectively used to control stress and anxiety, relieve insomnia, and reduce symptoms of certain types of chronic pain. Progressive muscle relaxation is based upon the simple practice of tensing, or tightening, one muscle group at a time followed by a relaxation phase with release of the tension. Use the University of Michigan Progressive Muscle Relaxation, https://www.uofmhealth.org/health-library/uz2225, or another favorite.
text:
Wellness Wednesday Tip from Health Teacher, Mr. Colasuonno: Complete 15 minutes of stress management activities daily.

Guided meditation is simply "meditation with the help of a guide". It’s one of the easiest ways to enter into a state of deep relaxation and inner stillness, and it’s one of the most powerful ways to eliminate stress and bring about positive personal changes. Use UCLA Guided Meditation, https://www.uclahealth.org/marc/mindful-meditations, or another favorite.
Progressive muscle relaxation is a deep relaxation technique that has been effectively used to control stress and anxiety, relieve insomnia, and reduce symptoms of certain types of chronic pain. Progressive muscle relaxation is based upon the simple practice of tensing, or tightening, one muscle group at a time followed by a relaxation phase with release of the tension. Use the University of Michigan Progressive Muscle Relaxation, https://www.uofmhealth.org/health-library/uz2225, or another favorite.

The State Education Department identified Tuckahoe High School for the second consecutive year as a School of Recognition. THS is among selected schools across New York State recognized for high achievement and performance.

“These are exemplary public schools that demonstrate that all students can achieve at high levels with the right supports and resources,” Board of Regents Chancellor Betty A. Rosa said. “Recognition Schools help to ensure equity for all children across New York State.”

We congratulate the teachers, administrators, staff, parents and students for the achievement. We congratulate the collaboration of all stakeholders, K-12, for the team effort towards a common vision of excellence for all.

Each Recognition School will receive a certificate of recognition from the Commissioner of Education.

Go Tigers!

Congratulations to the Tuckahoe's varsity boys and girls basketball teams!

The varsity boys team took the 42-38 win over Haldane on Monday night in the Class C semifinals. The boys will head to the Westchester County Center this Saturday - March 7 - to face off with Alexander Hamilton High School for the Class C Championship title at 12 p.m.

The varsity girls team won against Keio Academy on Wednesday night with a final score of 45-25 in the Class C semifinals. The girls will also head to the Wetchester County Center this Saturday at 2 p.m. to face off against Haldane for the Class C Championship title.

post_text: The Greenburgh Nature Center provided an informative presentation and activity about the journey of food. Our fifth-grade students built their own hydroponic system components. They learned what a food system is, where our food comes from, what pollinators are and why their role in our food system is so important, alternative methods to grow food for increased yields and decreased environmental impacts, and the affects that our food system has on the environment.

The first-ever Tuckahoe Athletics Cultural Luncheon took place last Wednesday at the Leffell School in Hartsdale. Its goal was to have the three team captains from each of the schools' varsity boys soccer teams come together to learn more about one another’s school cultures over lunch.

The Tuckahoe’s athletes who attended were Franz Vacca, Jason Macas and Jack Doherty. Coach Sweeney and Athletic Director Tobin accompanied them.

There are plans to have the captains' Cultural Luncheon continue in the future with our girls varsity soccer team and both of our varsity basketball teams hosting Leffell’s team. A special thanks to Dr. Linehan, Mr. DeBellis and Ms. Goodman for their support in making this happen.

The Tuckahoe’s athletes who attended were Franz Vacca, Jason Macas and Jack Doherty. Coach Sweeney and Athletic Director Tobin accompanied them.

The Tuckahoe Union Free School District Board of Education is beginning its search for the next Superintendent of Schools. We are seeking community members' views concerning the qualities that are most important in a new superintendent. Interested members of the Tuckahoe and school communities can complete and submit an online survey, which will be available until Dec. 11, 2019, by accessing the following link: https://www.surveymonkey.com/r/CNP7KKC

In addition, a public forum for all interested community members will be held at 6 p.m. on Dec. 13, 2019 in the Tuckahoe Middle/High School auditorium.

post_text: Earlier this week, Cottle's fourth-graders participated in a Journey into American Indian Territory workshop. Sponsored by the PTA, students participated in hands-on lessons about Native American life and culture through traditional games, song and dance, a clay workshop and a museum presentation featuring artifacts and a large-scale model longhouse. This multi-sensory workshop incorporates curriculum, language acquisition, and fine and gross motor skills.

Principal Mr. Morash and Assistant Principal Mr. Kilgallen recently announced the names of the first winners of the new William E. Cottle Orange Bandana Award! The WEC Orange Bandana Award is an honor that will be given this year to special fifth-grade students who have distinguished themselves by voluntarily performing outstanding acts of kindness, by being willing to help fellow students or by taking a stand against behavior that makes others feel bad. The winners are nominated by their peers and their teachers. Congratulations to the following Orange Bandana Award winners:
- Sophia M. – Made sure a student that did not have lunch got lunch.
- Andrew C. – Helped a classmate carry a big instrument and case down the hill when she was having trouble.
- Isabella S. – Stood up for a friend when others were not treating her nicely.

post_text:
As part of Ms. Caneparo's STEAM lessons this week, third-grade students collaborated to construct candy corn towers using candy corn and toothpicks. Students learned how important and strong the triangular shape is for building bridges, and they transferred this information to the building challenge.

Additionally, in a follow-up to a lesson on budgeting and resources, fourth-grade students participated in a "pumpkin man lesson," in which they were required to build a body that would hold a pumpkin as the head using the least amount of resources possible. Before building, students worked in small groups to plan their designs and estimate how many resources they would need. They then had 20 minutes to build before testing their bodies by placing a pumpkin on top to see if it held!

Students in Tuckahoe High School's digital art and design class are creating typography portraits using the manipulation of type focusing on font, size and placement to create values in their artwork.

The digital art and design elective is a new course offering this school year, the curriculum for which was designed through a Learning Technology Grant in partnership with Putnam-Northern Westchester BOCES. This three-year NYSED grant is designed to build the capacity of school districts to develop and deliver high-quality and authentic blended learning experiences for students.

Taught by Ms. Cacace, the course is a one semester blended learning elective that is focused on the artistic world through graphic design in preparation for post-secondary studies, employable skills and/or careers in the visual arts. Students will apply their enhanced skills, techniques and ideas using software applications such as Adobe Illustrator while blending a traditional face-to-face classroom setting with online learning.

Tuckahoe Middle School's 7th- and 8th-grade Diversity Club members welcomed 6th-graders by introducing themselves during their lunch period on Friday. Coinciding with Bullying Prevention Month, the activity provides 6th-graders with familiar faces and a warm, friendly atmosphere as they become acclimated to their new school.

In a larger endeavor to foster friendships and collegiality, the club participated in National Mix It Up Day yesterday. The initiative encouraged Tuckahoe Middle School students to meet new people by sitting somewhere different than usual at lunch. Upon entering the cafeteria, students encountered tables decorated with signs indicating various areas of interest including sports, gaming, baking, literature and STEM. Students were encouraged to sit at a table that peaked their interest, while Diversity Club members distributed buttons, bookmarks and bracelets to further spark conversation.

post_text: The first furniture in the complete refurbishment of the TMS/THS library space has been installed! The new small group instruction nook is a learning space for small groups, either student- or teacher-led, that promotes collaboration and active learning. The more dynamic library furniture encourages multi-disciplinary classwork that infuses technology and innovation into research and problem-solving.

post_text: Yesterday, Tuckahoe Middle School students shared their curiosities by participating in the Club Fair. Around 14 were represented, including the longstanding Diversity Club, as well as the new Debate Club and GSA Club. The children toured from table to table, learning about each. Principal Greg Stiefel said that many students participate in multiple clubs throughout the year. The clubs encourage them to learn more about their interests and meet new friends.

CONGRATULATIONS: Senior Justin Lee was named lohud's football "Player of the Week." This recognition coincided with his performance during Homecoming Week.

"His play at quarterback led Tuckahoe to a 40-16 home victory. Lee managed 161 yards and three touchdown passes on just seven completions and added 61 yards and a pair of touchdowns on the ground."

Tuckahoe High School's annual College Fair kicked off another college application season on Sept. 26. Coordinated by the THS guidance department, the event allowed juniors and seniors to interact with representatives from over 60 institutions of higher education.

"It is another opportunity for them to gather information and reflect on their near future," said THS Principal Bart Linehan.
